(Knight)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="82.[93,620,212,1758]" pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
<keyLead pageId="82" pageNumber="82">– Dorsal vestiture shorter, moderately dense to moderately sparse.................. 16</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
<paragraph blockId="82.[93,620,212,1758]" pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
<keyLead pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
16. Apex of hind femur (sharp delineation) and tibia yellow (fig. 12); male genitalia as in figures 15A–J and 16A–D................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Knight)" baseAuthorityName="Knight" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[418,619,639,659]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ambrosiae">
<emphasis box="[418,521,639,659]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="82">ambrosiae</emphasis>
(Knight)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="82.[93,620,212,1758]" pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
<keyLead pageId="82" pageNumber="82">– Apex of hind femur (diffuse delineation or wide) and tibia orange.............. 17</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
<paragraph blockId="82.[93,620,212,1758]" pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
<keyLead pageId="82" pageNumber="82">
17. Dorsal lobe of endosomal spicule twisted at base (fig. 45A–C); antennal segment II shorter than foretibia; additional male genitalia as in figure 46A–L.......... 
<taxonomicName authority="Knight" authorityName="Knight" box="[446,619,800,820]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sheridani">
